Intention is essential to iniuria : ‘ pati quis iniuriam etiamsi non sentiat potest, facere neme, nisi qui scit se iniuriam facere, etiamsi nesciat cui faciat ’ Dig. 47. 10. 3. 2 3 hence those were held incapable of committing iniuria who could not have such intention, e. g. persons of weak or un- sound mind, and children not yet doli capaces·

§ 1. The second condition of iniuria is an overt act, which, as is said in the text, might be directed against the person or the reputation ε ‘iniuriam autem fieri Labeo ait aut re, aut verbis: re, quotiens manus inseruntur, verbis autern, quotiens non manus( inferuntur, convicium fit ε omnemque iniuriam aut in corpus inferri, aut ad dignitatem aut ad infamiam pertinere’ Dig. 47. ιο. 1. 1 and 2. Among acts which amount to iniuria, besides those mentioned in the text, are calling upon sureties to discharge a debt which the debtor is quite able and willing to pay himself, Dig. ib. 19 and 203 offering for sale another’s property under the pretence that one has a mortgage over it, ib. 15. 32 and 333 the publication of a will whose provisions one should have kept secret, Dig. 9. 2. 41. pr.; unwarranted entry upon another man’s dwelling against his will, Dig. 47. 10. 5. pr.; hindei-ing another in the use os a

‘res publico usui destinata’ ib. 13. 7, and unjustifiable questioning of another's status, ib. 11. 9.

The technical name for libel is carmen or libellus famosus ; for slander there seems to have been no other term but convicium, which includes acts which we should call by other names. If such statements were true, and not made in an offensive manner, they did not amount to iniuria: ‘eum qui nocentem infamavit, non esse bonum aequum ob eam rem condemnari : peccata enim nocentium nota esse et oportere et expedire ³ Dig. 47. 10. 18. pr.
